      <h1>Nmap Recon Guide: How to See the Machines Around You</h1>

      <p>If you're on a Red Team mission â€” even a simulated one â€” your first task is simple: <strong>see the invisible</strong>. Before touching a port or probing a service, you need to know what's around. Here's how to do that with one of Kali Linux's most powerful tools: <code>nmap</code>.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ¯ Objective: Discover All Active Devices on a Network</h2>
      <p>Imagine you're dropped into a network with no map, no beacon, just your instincts and tools. You donâ€™t know who's there â€” but you need to.</p>
      <p><strong>Nmap</strong> can scan your local environment and list all live machines: laptops, smartphones, routers, IoT devices, you name it.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ§  Step 1 â€“ Know Your Own IP and Subnet</h2>
      <pre><code>ip a</code></pre>
      <p>Look for a line like:</p>
      <pre><code>inet 192.168.1.23/24</code></pre>
      <p>This means your IP is <code>192.168.1.23</code> and your subnet is <code>/24</code>, aka <code>192.168.1.0 - 192.168.1.255</code>.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ“¡ Understanding Hosts, Ports & Services</h2>

      <h3>ğŸ§ Host</h3>
      <p>A host is any machine connected to the network â€” a PC, a smartphone, a printer, or even a smart lightbulb. Each host has an IP address on the network (like <code>192.168.1.42</code>).</p>

      <h3>ğŸ”Œ Ports</h3>
      <p>A port is like a virtual door on a host. It's where services run and communicate. Ports are numbered from 0 to 65535. Some common ones:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>22</strong> â€“ SSH (remote login)</li>
        <li><strong>80</strong> â€“ HTTP (web server)</li>
        <li><strong>443</strong> â€“ HTTPS (secure web)</li>
        <li><strong>21</strong> â€“ FTP (file transfer)</li>
        <li><strong>3389</strong> â€“ RDP (Windows remote desktop)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Ports can be:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Open</strong> â€“ service is listening</li>
        <li><strong>Closed</strong> â€“ nothing is there</li>
        <li><strong>Filtered</strong> â€“ blocked by firewall or security tool</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>âš™ï¸ Services</h3>
      <p>A service is the actual software running behind a port. For example:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Port 22 might run <strong>OpenSSH</strong></li>
        <li>Port 80 could be <strong>Apache</strong> or <strong>Nginx</strong></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Nmap doesn't just detect ports â€” it can identify the service and sometimes its version (<code>Apache 2.4.41</code> for example).</p>

      <h2>ğŸ›°ï¸ Step 2 â€“ Ping Scan the Whole Network</h2>
      <pre><code>nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24</code></pre>
      <p>This will send ping requests to all 254 possible hosts. You'll get a list of machines that respond.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ“¦ Output Example</h2>
      <pre><code>Nmap scan report for 192.168.1.1 (Router)
Host is up.
Nmap scan report for 192.168.1.42 (Ubuntu-MSI)
Host is up.
Nmap scan report for 192.168.1.74
Host is up.</code></pre>

      <h2>ğŸ§© Step 3 â€“ Scan Detected Hosts One by One</h2>
      <p>Once you identify IPs, scan their ports and services:</p>
      <pre><code>nmap -sV -O 192.168.1.42</code></pre>
      <p>This reveals what the device is running â€” HTTP server, SSH, Samba, RDP, etc. Even OS fingerprinting.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ“‚ Optional: Save Results for Logs</h2>
      <pre><code>nmap -sn 192.168.1.0/24 -oN scan_results.txt</code></pre>
      <p>You can integrate the output into HyugaLog or a Red Team report later.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ›¡ï¸ Use Case â€“ Red Team Simulation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>You've breached a network but need passive intel first</li>
        <li>You're training OSINT and need to map a lab network</li>
        <li>You want to alert a team on how visible their devices are</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>âš ï¸ Ethics Reminder</h2>
      <p><strong>Never scan networks you donâ€™t own or have explicit permission to test.</strong></p>
      <p>Nmap is powerful, but with great power comes operational responsibility.</p>

      <h2>ğŸ“Œ Final Note</h2>
      <p>Scanning is not just technical. It's psychological. You're not looking at machines â€” you're reading a system's posture, assumptions, weaknesses. You're entering someone else's territory. Map it well.</p>

